column2: Longtail IOTC case study T. Carruthers

column3: DCAC input: this average catch from 1998-2010 corresponding with the Nishida index
DCAC input: This is the depletion from 1998-2010 inferred from Tom Nishidas cpue data - an xls file in this directory
Long tail supporting information puts this at 0.39 (0.29 – 0.54) which is ~ FMSY_M of 0.66. Martell and Walters 2009 think between 0.5 and 0.75 so this seems reasonable.
Also a generic ratio for most bill fish and tunas

MSY estimate is simply mean catches (note that in MSE testing most MPs perform very similarly even  if they use real MSY and average catches interchangeably - mostly because it is depletion information that determines management success: see Harford and Carruthers 2017)
A simple calculation based on inputs above BMSY = MSY / (-ln(1-M*FMSY_M)) (but highly uncertain - see CV_BMSY below)
A rough guess based on the 10% slope seen in a large fraction stocks
This is current length at full selection: must be higher than modal length comp due to declining frequency of population numbers with size
Needs a reliable index going back to 1950 (none available) or needs intepretation of the length comp data ie by Stochastic SRA or similar
Consistent with length at 1 between 40-46 cm: longtail supporting information.pdf
Assumed zero as skipjack (skipjack pdf in this folder)
